  <h2>Quick Navigation</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="#workflow">Recommended Workflow</a></li>
    <li><a href="#entries">Timeline Entries</a></li>
    <li><a href="#characters">Characters</a></li>
    <li><a href="#sources">Sources</a></li>
    <li><a href="#tips">Tips for Writers</a></li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="help-section" id="workflow">
  <h2>Recommended Workflow</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <p>For best results, follow this order when adding new research:</p>
    <ol class="help-steps">
      <li>
        <strong>Add the Source first</strong><br>
        Before documenting any events, create a record for the book, article, or documentary you're reading. This allows you to link entries back to their origin.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add Characters as you encounter them</strong><br>
        When you come across a new person in your research, add them to the Characters database before creating entries that involve them.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Create Timeline Entries</strong><br>
        Document events as you read, linking them to the source and any characters involved.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Mark entries as Verified</strong><br>
        When you find the same event confirmed in multiple sources, mark it as verified to indicate higher confidence.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="help-section" id="entries">
  <h2>Timeline Entries</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <p>Timeline entries are the core of your research database. Each entry represents a specific event or moment in Onassis's life.</p>

    <h3>Required Fields</h3>
    <table class="help-table">
      <tr>
        <td><span class="field-required">Title</span></td>
        <td>A clear, concise title for the event. Be specific enough that writers can quickly identify what happened.<br>
        <em>Examples: "Marriage to Tina Livanos", "Purchase of Olympic Airways", "First meeting with Maria Callas"</em></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><span class="field-required">Event Date</span></td>
        <td>The date the event occurred. If you only know the year, use January 1st of that year and note the uncertainty in the description.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>Optional Fields</h3>
    <table class="help-table">
      <tr>
        <td><strong>End Date</strong></td>
        <td>For events spanning multiple days (trips, negotiations, affairs). Leave blank for single-day events.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Event Type</strong></td>
        <td>Categorize the event for filtering. Available types:
          <div class="tag-list">
            <% Entry::ENTRY_TYPES.each do |type| %>
              <span class="tag"><%= type.titleize %></span>
            <% end %>
          </div>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Location</strong></td>
        <td>Where the event took place. Include city and country.<br>
        <em>Examples: "Athens, Greece", "Monte Carlo, Monaco", "Aboard the Christina, Mediterranean"</em></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Description</strong></td>
        <td>Detailed account of what happened. Include relevant context, quotes, and specific details from your source.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Historical Significance</strong></td>
        <td><span class="tag tag-type">For Writers</span> This field is specifically for noting the dramatic potential of the event. What makes this compelling for the series? How might it be portrayed?</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>People Involved</strong></td>
        <td>Select all characters who were present or directly involved in the event. You can select multiple characters.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Sources</strong></td>
        <td>You can add <strong>multiple sources</strong> for each entry. This is especially useful when the same event is documented in different books or articles. For each source you can specify:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Source:</strong> Select from your source database</li>
            <li><strong>Page Reference:</strong> The specific page(s) in that source</li>
            <li><strong>Notes:</strong> How this source specifically covers the event</li>
          </ul>
          Click "Add Another Source" to cite additional sources for the same event.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Verified</strong></td>
        <td>Check this box when the event has been confirmed by multiple independent sources. Leave unchecked for single-source information or uncertain details.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="help-section" id="characters">
  <h2>Characters</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <p>Characters are the people who interacted with Aristotle Onassis throughout his life. Building a comprehensive character database helps track relationships and makes it easy to see all events involving a specific person.</p>

    <h3>Required Fields</h3>
    <table class="help-table">
      <tr>
        <td><span class="field-required">Name</span></td>
        <td>The person's full name as commonly known. Use the name they're most recognized by.<br>
        <em>Examples: "Jacqueline Kennedy" (not "Jacqueline Lee Bouvier Kennedy Onassis"), "Maria Callas" (not "Maria Anna Cecilia Sofia Kalogeropoulos")</em></td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>Optional Fields</h3>
    <table class="help-table">
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Relationship</strong></td>
        <td>How this person relates to Onassis. Available types:
          <div class="tag-list">
            <% Character::RELATIONSHIPS.each do |rel| %>
              <span class="tag"><%= rel.titleize %></span>
            <% end %>
          </div>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Date of Birth</strong></td>
        <td>The person's birth date, if known.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Date of Death</strong></td>
        <td>The person's death date, if applicable and known.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Nationality</strong></td>
        <td>The person's nationality or country of origin.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Occupation</strong></td>
        <td>What the person was known for. Can include multiple roles.<br>
        <em>Examples: "Shipping Magnate", "Opera Singer", "First Lady, Editor"</em></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Biography / Notes</strong></td>
        <td>Background information about the person, their significance to Onassis's life, and any notes relevant to the series.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>Relationship Types Explained</h3>
    <dl class="help-definitions">
      <dt>Family</dt>
      <dd>Blood relatives and immediate family members (children, parents, siblings)</dd>
      <dt>Business</dt>
      <dd>Business partners, associates, employees, competitors in commerce</dd>
      <dt>Romantic</dt>
      <dd>Spouses, lovers, romantic interests</dd>
      <dt>Political</dt>
      <dd>Politicians, government officials, diplomats</dd>
      <dt>Social</dt>
      <dd>Friends, social acquaintances, celebrities in his circle</dd>
      <dt>Rival</dt>
      <dd>Direct competitors, enemies, antagonists</dd>
      <dt>Employee</dt>
      <dd>Staff, crew members, household employees</dd>
      <dt>Other</dt>
      <dd>Anyone who doesn't fit the above categories</dd>
    </dl>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="help-section" id="sources">
  <h2>Sources</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <p>Tracking your sources is essential for verifying information and allowing writers to dig deeper into specific events.</p>

    <h3>Required Fields</h3>
    <table class="help-table">
      <tr>
        <td><span class="field-required">Title</span></td>
        <td>The full title of the book, article, or documentary.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>Optional Fields</h3>
    <table class="help-table">
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Author</strong></td>
        <td>The author or creator of the source.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Type</strong></td>
        <td>The format of the source:
          <div class="tag-list">
            <% Source::SOURCE_TYPES.each do |type| %>
              <span class="tag"><%= type.titleize %></span>
            <% end %>
          </div>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Publisher</strong></td>
        <td>The publishing company or media outlet.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Publication Date</strong></td>
        <td>When the source was published or released.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Notes / Summary</strong></td>
        <td>Your assessment of the source: reliability, bias, key themes covered, overall quality. This helps writers evaluate how much weight to give information from this source.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="help-section" id="tips">
  <h2>Tips for Writers</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <h3>Using the Timeline View</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Use the <strong>decade filter</strong> to focus on specific eras (e.g., the 1960s for the Maria Callas affair and Jackie Kennedy marriage)</li>
      <li>Use the <strong>event type filter</strong> to find all business deals, marriages, or scandals</li>
      <li>Use the <strong>character filter</strong> to see all events involving a specific person</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The Significance Field</h3>
    <p>When adding entries, the "Historical Significance" field is your space to note:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Why this event matters dramatically</li>
      <li>Potential scene ideas or visual moments</li>
      <li>Connections to other events or characters</li>
      <li>Themes this event could explore</li>
      <li>Which season/episode this might fit into</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Verification Status</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><span class="tag tag-verified">Verified</span> - Confirmed by multiple independent sources. Safe to use as established fact.</li>
      <li><span class="tag tag-unverified">Unverified</span> - Single source or conflicting accounts. May need dramatic license or further research.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Search Tips</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Search finds matches in titles, descriptions, character names, biographies, source titles, and notes</li>
      <li>Use specific terms for better results (e.g., "Monaco" instead of "casino")</li>
      <li>Search for character names to find all mentions across entries</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

